        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Where this dish lives",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Chip shop curry sauce became popular in the 1970s, especially in the North of England, the Midlands, and Scotland. It is not an Indian curry sauce adapted for chips. It is a British invention, built on mild curry powder that had been in British kitchens since the Victorian era. It now sits on every chip shop menu, served alongside gravy as the two great options for topping a portion of chips.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
